PROJECT 5: Communicate Data Findings

Loan Data

Introduction:¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.
The aim of the data analysis is to provide a graphical summary of important features of the data set and predicting the Loan outcome in the dataset.

6. ProsperRating (Alpha)¶

The Prosper Rating assigned at the time the listing was created between AA - HR. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009. The rating assigned by Prosper helps to decide the APR the borrower should be charged.

In [313]:

Note:Loans with "AA" category are with lesser count

7. ProsperScore¶

A custom risk score was built using historical Prosper data to assess the risk of Prosper borrower listings. The output to Prosper users is a Prosper score which ranges from 1 to 11, with 11 being the best, or lowest risk, score. The worst, or highest risk, score, is a 1.
Prosper uses both the custom score and the credit reporting agency score together to assess the borrowers level of risk and determine estimated loss rates. For detailed explanation:https://www.prosper.com/plp/general-prosper_score/

In [316]:
plt.figure(figsize=(7, 4))
base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
sns.countplot(data=loan_clean,x="ProsperScore",color=base_color)
Out[316]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x1bd4b587588>

Note: There are alot of borrower's with prosperScore less than 6.0. Based on this we can say loan was even provided to people with high risk score.
